w:r.w:t: I chose my maximum number of threads to be 10 because as the number got above that the multi-threaded function started to become slower than the single thread because it was having to wait on so many more threads to join. In my algorithm I am using a step size to help iterate through my matrix. I chose this specific pattern because it allowed me to split my matrix up amongst my threads in the best way I could figure without sacrificing too much efficiency.
My for loop that incorporated this goes like this:
c = step++; // this essentially is saying which thread
int i = c*N/number of threads // this says thread c starts i at c*N/number of threads
in the case of N = 10, number of threads = 10
i = 1, so as it iterates i becomes a multiplier for the row portion of row*col
sum += MATA[i * col + k] * MATB[k * col + j];
k and j are added to put it at the current position

The results are what I was expecting. Multi-threading seemed unnecessary to me when there were less than 100x100 objects in the matrices because at that point the computer’s processor is able to process them at the same or faster speed with a single thread. As the values increased past N=100 Multi-threading became needed because a single thread became slower and slower. Based on my results at N =100, multi-threading was 1.13x faster, but at N = 500, multi-threading was 1.62x faster and at N =1000 multi-threading was 2.036x faster than a single thread.
